<section xml:id="translation-glide">
    <title>Translation and Glide</title>
    
<ol>

<li><p>In this figure below, <m>\triangle ABC</m> has been translated once by <m>\overrightarrow{u}</m>, translated once by <m>\overrightarrow{v}</m> and reflected over <m>\overleftrightarrow{m}</m>. Do you think we can get from the left triangle to the right triangle in a single rigid motion?</p>
            <example>
            <figure xml:id="translation_glide-1">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/translation_glide-1.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's double translation, and reflection</caption>
           </figure>
           </example>
</li>

<li><p>Perhaps you have come to the conclusion that it is a translation and reflection. How would one go about finding the translation and mirror?
</p>
			<example>
            <figure xml:id="translation_glide-2">
<image source="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nickdowdall/Trans-geo/master/rigid_motions/other-stuff/pictures/new-pictures/translation_glide-2.png" width="90%"/>
<caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> and it's double translation, and whatever</caption>
           </figure>
           </example>
</li>

<li><p>The most direct way to find the translation is to find the vector between the starting and ending locations of the same point.</p>
